76561198009078453,Not Recommended,306040,26181204,"Posted: 23 October, 2016",all,Aurélien,"TL;DR: The Howler is a slow, extremely tedious game that will test your patience and relies on an art style that doesn't compliment nor is complimented by either the gameplay or the sound design, causing frustration (did I mention that you gotta wait for everything, even bringing the pause menu is slow) especially when using the gimmick, sound-based control feature.The Howler is another gimmick ""arty"" indie game that hides its more than shallow and lackluster gameplay behind supposedly stunning art and visuals; which I normally have no problem with but in this case the graphics are far from gorgeous:I presume it's supposed to fit into a certain art style given that (quote from the game's store page) ""All art used in the Howler was meticulously created by classically-trained experienced painters."" but this art style is not meant for games, it just doesn't work and looks like a scanned colored pencil piece of drawing. It has terrible affordance and does a very poor job at showing what element is going to pop the balloon and what is just part of the background.Still going on the art: the sound design is dull and repetitive, as if they forgot to implement any sound and rushed it at the last minute.I will however admit that the first time the balloon approaches the iron Wolf, and the jaw opens with a deep, metallic sound, it was pretty cool.The gameplay, even though not the most important part in this kind of game, barely exists: it's roughly clicking and waiting with little challenge other than testing your patience.The sound control gimmick (note that I'm consciously using the word gimmick rather than feature) is forgettable. It's not bad, but it's far from good. It's forgettable for the very reason that it has little to no gameplay to be applied on!And regarding the level design, I'm hesitant whether it has been made by someone with little experience or someone simply lazy: it's over-simplistic and very repetitive.As a conclusion I'd like to address some errors in the store page user-defined tags:- Adventure: No. It's certainly not an Adventure game.- Simulation: I can see why this tag, but it barely simulates anything.- Strategy: Oh please, strategy? No. Strategy is term that defines long-term thinking and process. Even the word ""tactical"" would be more fitting here.- Action: Ahah... If your definition of Action is: click-wait-click-wait-wait-wait-click... then yes, maybe.- Shoot 'Em Up: Oh come on! Now that's just blatant lies.- Sports: What the f...- Puzzle: Nope. The Howler is very simplistic so no thinking requiered.- Difficult: No. Tedious.I give this game the rating of 15/100"
,Recommended,306040,17487664,"Posted: 11 August, 2015",all,peter purvis,"A simple idea made great with awesome hand-rendered charcoal/paint/ink art. Looks easy at first but very quickly becomes a highly precise battle against the wind and gravity. Despite only running in a 4:3 black bordered box or window, The Howlers representation of a steam-punk Lithuanian capital Vilnius remains hugely atmospheric. Excellent."
