76561198348999904,Not Recommended,306040,33729171,Posted: 22 July,all,Optimistic Player,"Oh, this is going to be a long one. First let me tell you what I like aboutThe Howler:+) Nice art style/OST/general concept:Overall it makes a good first impression. Hand drawn sprites and backgrounds combined with soothing music are the perfect way to start a short break. As for the concept: The game seems to promote a SF novel, so I guess it contributed to some degree.+) Hm...Well, that was short enough. So now the cons:-) Slow gameplay:You move your air balloon sideways by horizontally separated zones, which have different wind directions and/or forces. The problem is that even the strongest wind accelerates you very slowly. That might be realistic, but it doesn't help to get a good pace going. It's also the main reason, why it took me a whole hour to completeThe Howler, which brings me to my next point...-) Shortness of the levels:Normally I wouldn't mind with such a cheap game, but the levels are really, really short. Imagine the first level of Super Mario Bros being over once you get the first mushroom. That short.-) Indoor levels:It's a minority of the 16 levels, but frustrating enough for me to mention them. The main problem is, that some parts of the walls will pop your air balloon, while others won't. However the indicators (really small spikes) are often indistinguishable from the background. The only way to learn where they  are is through trial & error.But you know what? Those aren't the reasons why I don't recommendThe Howler.I love how Steam has a lot of good, free games and I think thatThe Howlerwould fit perfectly in this category. But unfortunately it isn't for free. That's why I don't recommend it. It may sound mean, but a game with the quality & quantity of content asThe Howler(AND which is also mainly promotional material for a book/capital city) just isn't worth the 1€ (or 50 cents in my case).Additional note:There are apparently a lot of people, who experience bugs/glitches with this game. Levels not loading, the balloon not reacting to voice steering, game crashes and so on. I played this game on a normal PC with mouse control and didn't experience any of them."
,Recommended,306040,29117205,Posted: 8 January,all,[ZDG] Asix Seleven @Rage,"Even though this type of puzzler isn't for me, it is still a nice game.Not fond of the gamestyle, but controls are easy to understand and this game has a magnificent drawing style."
,Recommended,306040,22331597,"Posted: 9 April, 2016",all,Bumblebugbee3,"Life as air-balloon pilot is tough.  You aren't afforded any of those nifty steering doo-dads.  All you have to guide you is the wind.  Playing The Howler is all about learning to become one with the wind as you soar around this pastel world.  Its a simple concept for a game but it comes together quite well.  Its a short but sweet ride that should keep you entertained for just over an hour.The controls are super simple.  All you can do is increase the heat to ascend or subsequently release the hot air to descend.  By controlling the elevation you will pass through different zones of air blowing the wind this way and that way.  Certain currents will be stronger than other and you must be careful of the potential momentum of the stronger winds.  By straddling these currents you can proceed to your destination or pick up goods required for the different objectives.Many levels will simply have to going for one spot to another.  Other levels may have you pick up and deliver a package.  Later in the game you'll be given bombs you can drop.  Use these to destroy obstacles in your path or take out the enemy's bridge.  Just be careful not to be too close to your bombs as you can easily be sent floating off screen and into the abyss.One of the coolest parts of the game is the hand drawn art.  The backgrounds are gorgeous and rich with detail.  They distinguish themselves nicely from the sharp,clean, lines of the objects in the foreground.  There isn't much to the sound design.  There isn't any music while playing which could be justified to help you concentrate.  Usually all you hear is balloon's propane kicking in as you turn on the heat to ascend.  That being said the automatons and cars really stick out in the levels they're present.There really isn't much else to say.  This is a really simple game, one that doesn't take long to finish.  That isn't necessary a bad thing considering the low price point.  Not to mention there really isn't many other games like it.  The unique art style might make it worth considering if you're on edge.  As long as you're not expecting anything too fancy there is fun to be had playing The Howler."
