,Recommended,306040,24903005,"Posted: 13 August, 2016",all,TheQuantumTantrum,"I am quite fond of hand done art in a video game. It reminds me of where graphic art truly began. The Howler is a very interesting game that utilizes hand done art in most, if not all, of its assets. Based on the book Hour of the Wolf, the game is set in an alternate steampunk version of Vilnius, Lithuania.The Howler has a lot going for it. It is a physics game where you utilize wind current to move a hot air balloon to its destination. The Howler also allows you to use your voice as a form of game control. The length of The Howler is quite short, and due to that it is difficult to gain all the Steam Trading Cards without leaving it running. I did have a few bugs with the window and fullscreen, but I am able to look past that. My biggest complaint of The Howler is the platform I played it on. This is a mobile game, ported to the computer. I believe, because of that, I could not get into this game. I did complete it, however I never had fun. There was something pulling me away the experience, and I think it is because I could have played it on my phone.That being said, I would advise you to try The Howler out, but not for full price. Preferably, you should pick up The Howler when the Art Appreciation Pack goes on sale. The Art Appreciation Pack goes on sale once every few months, and the other games are quite interesting as well."
76561198047266382,Recommended,306040,19009555,"Posted: 11 November, 2015",all,[GC]SpiritWolf,"Awoo?Basic Breakdown: Developed by Antanas Marcelionis and Renė Petrulienė, published by Antanas Marcelionis The Howler is an adventure puzzle game with a set of interesting, unusual, unforgiving and complex puzzles that will have you frustrated many a times.You control your air balloon through a series of 'missions' to either deliver packages, blow up automatons or just land atop another air ship as the winds play havoc with your flight path.Pro Tip- To unlock the final puzzle, the code is -sos-Menu: Honestly, there isn't really one which is slightly bothersome. Especially when it comes to wanting to remap certain keys that are to do with steam. Taking screenshots while you have a package or a bomb will instantly release them, interfering with your mission.Graphics/Art: All art used in the Howler was meticulously created by classically-trained painters. Most of the art was thanks to Rene Petruliene: all the graphic design was drawn by hand, giving it that extra classic, renaissance feel.Soundtrack: It ties in with the aesthetics of the game so well. It gives it that timely atmospheric feel that just works.Final Conclusion: Great, fairly short puzzler that will keep you entertained and frustrated depending on how good you are at controlling your air balloon. Also has a nifty unique feature of being able to control your flight with voice/sound from your headset which I quite enjoy because it keeps things interesting.Completing a mission will leave you feeling satisfied and accomplished, which for me is very rare. Props to the devs for making such a well balanced game that is entertaining, has wonderful art that clearly shows a lot of work and initiative went into it, for making something really unique and a nice cross of difficult but not punishing.As must for any puzzle fans out there."
