,Recommended,306040,31052837,Posted: 9 April,all,« Ralph »,"This game features an interesting and unique art style that gives a warm, yet delightfully bleak impression due to its limited color palette of autumn colors. This wonderfully rich world is painted with a variety of shades, including earthly reds, moody oranges and warm bronze. In my opinion, the interesting choice of colour represents a particular time of day when winds are most calm to traverse along with a traditional autumn season.The culture of the narrative is represented mainly in it's architecture, which are presented as obstacles throughout the game. These buildings are very detailed and is clearly the work of a talented artist. Unfortunately, apart from on-screen text that shows the player's objective and motivations, the building's style is the only visual means of connecting the player to the game world. This isn't necessarily a bad thing for such a short, independent title, but it leaves a strong desire to dive deeper into it's limited narrative once all levels are completed.The game is almost entirely played with a single tap of a mouse or screen, with the exception of the spacebar. Despite it's simple mechanics, the gameplay can be very challenging at certain levels. Espically at the beginning of the game, where the pilot is tasked to fly beyond a collosal monstrosity of a howling wolf to retrieve a set of packages before returning to the glorious canine to descend into it's steel belly.The hour that you will typlically spend playing 'The Howler' will be an artisticaly inspirational and rewarding hour. I would gladly reccommend the game for anyone who appreciates art or has a simple hour to spend."
76561198022266051,Recommended,306040,23075937,"Posted: 18 May, 2016",all,OakenPants,"It's a game with nice art, but unfortunately that's about it.The gameplay is OK.  All you can do is control the fire (aka lift) of the balloon which raises and lowers it.  Doing this, puts the balloon in different ""zones"" of wind travelling in different directions and speeds (indicated by arrows on left of screen).  Using the wind to move around, the goal is simply to land at a particular location, and on some levels pickup a package/bomb or drop a package/bomb onto something before landing.  Simple idea and each level takes only a couple minutes to complete.There's15 campaign missions which I completed in exactly one hourand one unique bonus level good for another cool 5 minutes of play BUT you have to enter a password first.  The game tells you that the password is given to you by a tower, but then doesn't tell you on which of the 15 levels the tower is....uh...so instead of playing another hour, I just googled the password...the password is:SOSOverall:  It's a nice / pretty game for an hour, but there's really not much here.  7 out of 10."
