,Not Recommended,306040,22505822,"Posted: 18 April, 2016",all,DefiningSound,"Summary: I can't swallow the broken physics and without it there is no game.Right:Hot Air balloons can be controlled with a single ""burn"" input (one button), sending the hot-air balloon upwards. Think ""Flappy Bird"", not ""Kerbal SPace Program"".Wrong:The only thing that makes this a ""game"" (instead of a ""follow the arrows"" exercise) is that physics is twisted so that the balloon can gain momentum in one windstream, and when the balloon enters a different windstream, the balloon will briefly continue moving as though it were still in the first windstream. Neither Boyle, Bernoulli nor Newton would have approved this game-design decision. It's not how balloons work in air. And without this twist there is no game.Wrong:The player can hear the burn when the balloon is ordered to move upwards, suggesting a warm balloon filled with mostly Nitrogen and Carbon Dioxide. Yet the balloon detonates when it strikes an object, as thought the balloon were constructed of strike-anywhere matches and filled with hydrogen.Wrong:The balloon can go seemingly infinitely far off the map to the left, right, or bottom. But if it goes off the top of the map, it is ""lost"" and forces a restart. What, did it go into orbit? Doesn't the air on this planet get thinner with altitude?Wrong:No fuel meter, infinite burns are allowed. Fuel should have been the ""game"", and physics should have been real."
