,Not Recommended,306040,20627421,"Posted: 19 January, 2016",all,Double Uppercut,"I'm not really enjoying this so-called ""Art Appreciation"" pack. So far, the first two games just show artistic promise while having actual gameplay about as bad as trying to walk with tent poles for legs.The Howler (odd enough name, as the actual Howler is only in the first level), revolves around a city being thrust into madness... oh, you can't tell? The level design doesn't imply that? Yeah, see that's the big issue with games that rely on cutscenes or text to simply TELL you what's going on and not backing it up. It's like getting ready for a dinner party, and your friend tells you, ""Hey! Get ready! This is really high society. Act your best!"" And when you get in, dressed in your tuxedo, the place is actually a hillbilly hoedown. The world of The Howler feels very empty and lifeless, rather than tense and on the brink of destruction, like the so-called ""story"" would imply.I have some humongous problems with the gameplay (very similarly to Gravilon), being that momentum is NOT a good mechanic for a video game. It's simply too much of a semi-controllable variable that makes beating levels feel more like you got lucky rather than actually feeling like you accomplished and learned something. So many of these levels are agonizingly hard because of how semi-predictable the movement of your hot air balloon is.The world is designed just fine. I have no issues with it, visually. It certainly looks a lot more vivid than Gravilon, but again the design makes a lot of obstacles much harder than they are. Such as building up momentum to get over a fair-sized chimney proved to be a right pain in my a** after attempting the level about 15 times.If you like momentum games, and a decent challenge, The Howler will shortly satiate your starvation. But as for people looking for actual ""art""... I suggest you look over by Dear Esther or Elegy for a Dead World. There's very little art around here."
